problem:
\begin{problem*}{}{}
  Let $\{u_n\}_{n \ge 1}$ be a sequence of real numbers
  defined as $u_1 = 1$ and
  \[
    u_{n+1} = u_n + \frac{1}{u_n} \text{ for all $n \ge 1$}
  .\]
  Prove that $u_n \le \frac{3\sqrt{n}}{2}$ for all $n$.
\end{problem*}

solution:
\begin{soln}
  Note that $u_1\le \frac{3}{2}\sqrt{1}$.

  Also $u_2=u_1+\frac{1}{u_1}>0$. Similarly, if $u_i>0$, then
  $u_{i+1}=u_i +\frac{1}{u_i}>0$. So $u_1>0\implies u_2>0
  \implies \cdots$ and so on. This gives us that $u_i>0$ for
  all $i\ge 1$.

  Now note that for all $n\ge 2$, by AM-GM we get that,
  \[
  u_n = u_{n-1}+\frac{1}{u_{n-1}}\ge 2
  .\]

  \begin{claim*}
    $u_n \le \frac{3}{2}\sqrt{n}$ for all $n\ge 2$.
  \end{claim*}
  \begin{subproof}
    We proceed by using induction on $n$.
    \begin{itemize}
      \item \textbf{Base Case:} For $n=2$,
        $u_2 = 2 \le \frac{3}{2}\sqrt{2}$.
      \item \textbf{Induction Hypothesis:} Assume that our claim
        is true for some $n=k\ge 2$.
      \item \textbf{Inductive Step:} We prove the claim for
        $n=k+1$.
        \begin{align*}
          u_{k+1}^2
          &= u_k^2+\frac{1}{u_k^2}+2\\
          &\le \frac{9k}{4}+\frac{1}{2}+2\\
          &= \frac{9(k+1)}{4}
        .\end{align*}

        This gives us that $a_{k+1}\le \frac{3}{2}\sqrt{k+1}$
        and thus our induction is complete.\qedhere
    \end{itemize}
  \end{subproof}

  Hence with the proof of our claim and the case $n=1$, the
  problem is solved.
\end{soln}
